<HEADLINE>
Thoughts on the anniversary of Steve Biko's death
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> Moira de Swardt &lt;moir...@wol.co.za&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-09-13T07:15:00 </POSTDATE>
Last night, over tea at Gramadoelos after the show which had nothing
whatsoever to do with Biko at the Market Theatre, a group of us were
talking and it was mentioned that one of the shows that night was a
Steve Biko thing at the Market Laboratory.  I mentioned that way back
on 12 September 1977 (or even a few days later) I learned about the
death of a man that I had never known.  In fact I didn't even know of
him either.  I was politically naive.  I couldn't really understand
what an impact this had on our country, although I did realise it was
all about murder by police officers who had not only failed in their
duty to protect a prisoner in their care, but brought shame on
themselves and the entire system.  This was a system which I had never
really questioned at the time despite the recent Soweto Uprising which
touched my life so briefly the year before as a college student in
Cape Town.

My revelation apparently shocked my companions, some of whom were more
politically aware (well, one could hardly be *less* politically aware)
at that stage in their lives than I was.  It was mentioned that most
of us became politically literate as a result of various factors,
including the liberal mixing of black and white people as both
performers and audience at the Market Theatre.   I certainly wasn't
acquiring a liberal political education at RAU where I was studying at
the time.

I wonder if the last thirty years have made much difference to my
thinking?  Am I any more politically aware than I was thirty years
ago?  Am I more tuned in to what the masses are thinking?  Am I still
so caught up in my own lifestyle that, while recognising that it
represents a very small minority of people, I am incapable of
visualising life as others see it?

As I contemplated these questions I realised that the life of Steve
Biko was the more powerful for his martyrdom.  If he hadn't died as a
result of injuries inflicted on him by the police while he was in
their custody a new generation now wouldn't be hearing about him.  The
scary thing about this scenario is that without the death of Steve
Biko in 1977, the eventual process which lead to the peaceful change
of government in 1994, I - and others of my hue - might not be alive
to look back on the last thirty years.  A kind of fatalistic destiny
thought.

Ja, nee.  Just thoughts.
</POST>
