I always have problems with terms like &quot;politically aware&quot; because the
people who use them too often don't mean &quot;aware of what is going on in
the political sphere&quot; but really mean &quot;sides with me&quot; or, if you're
cynical like me, &quot;we are one-step removed from the facists&quot;.

I had an interesting conversation some years ago with somebody at
Earthlife Africa. I was starting to think that finding out more about
environmental issues was a good idea and Earthlife seemed to be the
bunch who were addressing such issues (this was the late 80s).

I gave them a call and expressed interest.

They asked about my party political affiliations and I asked them what
the heck that had to do with the environment?

The reply was that Earthlife were a &quot;politically aware&quot; organisation.
I then asked if they actually believed that membership of a specific
party meant that one was more or less concerned with environmental
issues, and further asked if they didn't think it would be
constructive to reach people across the political concerned about the
environment and perhaps allow these people to find some common ground.

So the person at the other end asked who I'd voted for in the last
election.

By now I was peeved and smelt a rat and feeling a tad mischievous, so
I said &quot;KP&quot;.

I was told &quot;don't bother applying for membership&quot;.

But if we're talking about being aware of what is going on around one,
and degrees of awareness, then I must congratulate you on at least
knowing, at the time, that Biko had died whilst in custody.

Several people that I know claim that at the time they didn't know
anything about political prisoners dying in custody or even that there
WERE political prisoners, that there was a system called apartheid,
that there were laws that entrenched discrimination and disadvantaged
South Africans on the basis of skin colour etc etc.

I find this hard to believe, but then I can remember conversations I
had with various people in the 70s and 80s in which the risible and
scurrilous claims that I made about things like there being a seperate
education system and policy for black South Africans were given the
pooh-poohing that they deserved and were denounced as lies.

So there you go...
