politically aware, party reason to believe that I had voted
Conservative.

I was living in Yeoville at the time. Round about that time there'd
been a &quot;Yeoville Resident's Association&quot; formed to represent the
interests of the good people of Yeoville. And there was a Yeoville
Mardi Gras. And it was announced that at the Mardi Gras in the year in
question there would be a &quot;Speakers Corner&quot;.

Now I am seldom short of an opinion and decided to take myself along
to said Speakers Corner. I had an idea about what was really going on
- I was more right than I thought.

Turned out that the Speakers Corner was run by said residents
association - and that nobody could speak without YRA approval. So I
asked for permission to speak, assuring them that I was indeed a
resident, had been for many years, was not intoxicated and would do my
best to not overrun whatever allocation of time I was given. Well, of
course (and silly old me and all that) my application hadn't been
ratified by the YRA executive.

Which got me onto another subject: Who were the YRA, who was on the
executive and who chose them. After all, I'd live in Yeoville for
years and nobody had asked me to nominate or vote for anybody and I
really couldn't recall any public meetings or information campaigns.

Well you'd think I had just emerged from the deepest bowels of hell.
Why did I need to know who was on the executive, or ask questions
about how they got appointed? What was I? A Nat?

So I thanked them for their time and informed them that I was going to
try and find some other organisation that understood a little bit
about democracy.

Then they got really cross....
