I know it is a somewhat different thing, but I was fascinated to learn
from a colleague who does volunteer work with school debating just how
much this has progressed since my childhood. An example of the sort of
thing is at:

http://learn.uvm.edu/wdi/?Page=about.html

When I was at at school I was, of course, involved in debating
societies from prep school. I loved the process, but it was all very
amateur. We'd have the odd inter-school debates, but there was no
proper judging or review of the skills, something I found searious
lacunae even then. I wasn't happy that it was left up to simple voting
- I'm not a democrat as you know, so I always thought that a more
interesting metric of the quality of a debate would be the difference
in votes on a topic before and after a debate, rather than simply a
vote taken at the end that might simply reflect either entrenche
positions on the matter or partisan voting for your own side, rather
than on the matter. I longed for somebody credible to provide a
critique afterwards, to provide material for improvement.

Now the matter is far more formal and competitive with leagues and
championships that lead to international debating competitions.
Absolutely brilliant, in my view. I've wondered what is going on in
Cape Town in this matter and whether I could get involved with it.

Public speaking is fun and and important skill for children to
develop, I think, even in these days of e-mail. There's an even
stronger argument, I think for honing skills in arguing for positions
and using the various logical and rhetorical devices.
